<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     01-08 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peru Rekindles Anti-Inflation Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday pushed forward its
efforts to cool triple-digit inflation with measures that included a
28.5 percent devaluation of the currency.
   The package, which took effect Saturday, is the third in a series
of devaluations and austerity measures since September. They are
aimed at controlling rampaging inflation, which hit an all-time high
of 1,722 percent last year.
   In the latest measures, the center-left, populist government of
President Alan Garcia devalued the Peruvian inti from 500 to 700 to
the dollar, lifted the price of basic foods an average of 60
percent, and boosted salaries for most workers by 30 percent,
according to the government paper La Cronica.
   ``This third package of measures forms part of a policy to
progressively reduce inflation, while promoting exports and slowly
diminishing food subsidies,'' Economy Minister Carlos Rivas said in
announcing the program late Friday night.
   He has predicted the 1988 inflation figure will be cut by half
this year.
   But independent economists say the program has not gone far
enough in reducing the government's heavy spending policies. They
forecast inflation this year of at least 6,000 percent.
   The official rate valued the inti at 33 to the dollar before the
September devaluation.
   Analysts say rocketing inflation coupled with a dramatic
shrinkage of the economy last year, estimated at 8.4 percent, have
hit Peru's working class and its poor the hardest.
   They say the deteriorating economy and an eight-year insurgency
by leftist guerrillas have undermined government stability. Rumors
of a pending military coup have periodically sprung up in recent
months.
   The economic woes began to mount late in 1987 when dollar
reserves dried up and the government continued its spending program
despite a widening fiscal and trade deficits, a cutback in
investment and lack of fresh loans to bolster the dollar reserves.
   In Ayacucho, 225 miles southeast of Lima, police said Saturday
that Mao-inspired Shining Path guerrillas used explosives and
machine guns to ambush and kill three policeman in a jeep.
   Officials say rebel violence claimed nearly 2,000 lives last year
and more than 12,000 since 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
