<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0608 01-08 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Willes obit; AMs separate on Furillo moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Jean Willes</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VAN NUYS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jean Willes, who appeared in such
films as ``Elmer Gantry'' and the ``Perry Mason'' and ``Bonanza''
television series in her 30-year career, died Tuesday of liver
failure. She was 65.
   From the 1940s to the 1970s, Willes appeared in films such as
1958's ``No Time for Sergeants'' with Andy Griffith, the 1956 cult
classic ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers,'' ``Elmer Gantry'' in 1960
with Burt Lancaster, and ``Gypsy'' in 1962 with Rosalind Russell.
   In 1956 she played opposite Clark Gable in ``The King and Four
Queens'' and one of her final movies was ``Bite the Bullet'' in 1975
with Gene Hackman.
   She also appeared in such television shows as ``Perry Mason,''
``Bonanza,'' ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' and ``Kojak.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Nicholas Furillo</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COATESVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicholas Furillo, a minor-league baseball
player and brother of former Brooklyn Dodgers outfielder Carl
Furillo, died Wednesday in Brandywine Hospital. He was 70.
   Born in Reading, he moved to Chester in 1940, where he remained
for most of his life until returning to Reading recently.
   He played for the Eastern Shore League's Class B baseball team in
Cambridge, Md. in 1940, according to the National Association of
Baseball in St. Petersburg.
   He was a welder for 28 years at Baldwin-Lima-Hamilton Corp.,
Eddystone, retiring in 1970. He also owned and operated Furillo's
Sandwich Shop in Chester for 22 years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Robb</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Donald Robb, a composer of
symphonies, expert on Hispanic folk music and former dean of the
University of New Mexico College of Fine Arts, died Thursday. He was
96.
   Robb, once a New York City lawyer with a corporate bond practice,
wrote nearly 100 surviving works. They include symphonies and other
orchestral works, string quartets and other chamber music,
electronic music and musical stage pieces.
   Robb founded UNM's Robb Archive of Southwestern Folk Music and
made the first field recording for the archive. He later published
the authoritative book on New Mexico's Hispanic folk music.
   In 1921 he married Harriet Block, who survives him.
   He moved to Albuquerque in 1941 to head the university's music
department. However, he became acting dean of the Fine Arts School
shortly after arriving, and became permanent dean in 1947.
   In 1960, he ran for Congress on the Republican Party ticket,
losing to Democrat Thomas Morris of Tucumcari by 25,000 votes.
   Born in 1892 in Minneapolis, Robb entered Yale in 1911 to study
English literature. He later studied law at the University of
Minnesota and Harvard.
</TEXT>
