<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     01-08 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamils Ambush Sri Lankan, Indian Army Trucks, Kill 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil guerrillas ambushed Sri Lankan
and Indian army patrols in two separate incidents that left at least
six soldiers and a civilian dead, military officials said Sunday.
   Three Sri Lankan soldiers were killed and three were seriously
wounded in an attack Saturday night near Padaviya, 145 miles
northeast of Colombo, said officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Guerrillas hiding in dense jungle on both sides of the road
opened fire with machine guns and pistols when the army truck
approached, they said. Afterward, the guerrillas fled into the
jungle with four Chinese-made T-56 semiautomatic rifles seized from
the truck, said the officials.
   The civilian driver also was killed.
   The officials said the attack was mounted by guerrillas of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil, the biggest of the Tamil separatist
groups fighting the Sri Lankan government.
   In the other attack, Tamil guerrillas killed three Indian
soldiers at Trincomalee, 147 miles northeast of Colombo on Saturday,
the officials said.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Militant Tamils seek an independent state in the northeastern part
of the island nation to combat what they say is discrimination by
Sinhalese, who dominate the government and comprise 75 percent of
the population.
   Indian peacekeeping troops were dispatched to Sri Lanka in July
1987 to try to disarm the Tigers, whose insurrection has claimed
more than 8,500 lives in six years.
   Last week, India began withdrawing some of its 50,000 troops from
the island. One battalion of 2,500 to 3,000 men has left.
   More will be withdrawn in phases ``depending on the situation on
the ground,'' according to an Indian diplomat who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</TEXT>
