<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     01-08 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korean Art Works Imported, First Direct Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 600 North Korean art works
have arrived in South Korea, marking the first direct trade between
the two rival Korean states, government officials said Sunday.
   The paintings and pottery worth $104,000 were imported by Daewoo
Corp. of Seoul in a direct deal with a North Korean trading firm,
said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   It was the first direct deal between the two Koreas since the
Seoul government lifted a ban on trade with North Korea in October
as part of its new policy of seeking improved relations with the
communist state.
   The art works will be sold to the public after display at major
department stores in Seoul and other cities, the officials said.
They did not say how the goods arrived in South Korea, but they are
believed to have been transported by ship via a third country.
   The government has said no duties would be levied on imports from
North Korea because they would be regarded as internal trade.
   Several other trading houses in Seoul are reportedly moving to
import fish, coal and other industrial raw materials from North
Korea under the new government policy, the officials said.
   They said direct trade between the two Koreas is expected to
increase as North Korea appears to be willing to open its society to
the outside world. The two Koreas were divided in 1945.
   Chung Ju-yung, honorary chairman of South Korea's giant Hyundai
group, has been invited to visit North Korea to discuss investment
and other development projects there.
   Chung, originally from North Korea, said before his departure for
the Soviet Union last week that he would discuss investment in hotel
projects at Mount Diamond, a scenic tourist spot on North Korea's
east coast. His birthplace is near the mountain.
   In a related development, industry sources said Hyundai has
received a $270 million Soviet order to construct nine oil tankers
and multipurpose merchant ships in South Korea.
   The terms of the Soviet order, including financing, were not
disclosed, but the sources said they were related to Hyundai's plan
to participate in the development of Siberia.
   Chung is currently in the Soviet Union to discuss the deal, they
said. Before his departure for Moscow, Chung said he would visit
North Korea later this month.
</TEXT>
