<FIRST>r a AM-RestaurantHostages     01-08 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Restaurant Hostages,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restaurant Reopens After Fatal Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugs and tears marked the reopening of the
Riverhouse Restaurant, where a customer, a waitress and a gunman who
held 20 people hostage were shot to death four days earlier.
   All but three of the 35 employees showed up to greet customers
Saturday night at the restaurant after waitress Sally Mills and
customer Fenton Crookshank were killed in the bloody finale to
Tuesday night's siege.
   ``The next day I was ready to board this puppy up,'' said Bruce
Copp, who has owned the restaurant for two years. But the people of
Loveland, 35 miles northwest of Denver, held true to the city's name
and showered the restaurant staff with support.
   ``They have been non-stop in their calls of support,'' Copp said.
``That's probably one reason that we're going on.''
   The other reason is the strong bond among employees.
   Copp said his employees met to discuss their emotions after the
ordeal and decided to get back to work.
   Investigators say the gunman, Wayne Strozzi, apparently went
berserk after his estranged wife refused to go back to him. Police
say Strozzi then ambushed two law enforcment officers, wounding one,
before running into the restaurant and taking some 20 people hostage
Tuesday night.
   The siege ended when police shot Strozzi, who then apparently
killed Ms. Mills as he lay dying. Crookshank was accidentally killed
by police as he tried to escape through a window.
   When the restaurant's doors reopened Saturday, there were a few
hugs and a few tears as the regulars came in first. The phone rang
and rang.
   Copp, who said he was nervous about what to expect from the
customers, relaxed as the seafood and steaks started arriving at
tables.
   As he rang up his first sale Saturday at the cash register where
Strozzi took his first hostage Tuesday, Copp said it was like
starting over again.
   ``I feel like we're opening up for the first time,'' Copp said
with a smile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
