<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StateIssues-Glance 5Takes   01-08 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Issues-Glance, 5 Takes,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>State-By-State Wrapup Of Top Issues Before Legislatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-State Issues Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the top issues facing the 50 state
governments in 1989:
   Alabama: Tax reform has been placed at the top of Republican Gov.
Guy Hunt's agenda, but political paralysis may doom any efforts.
   Alaska: Because of the decline in oil revenues, the state is
facing an estimated $1 billion budget deficit that's expected to
mount over the next 18 months unless spending is cut.
   Arizona: The state must have a balanced budget, and it is agreed
that it will cost $300 million to $350 million over this year's $3
billion budget to fund current programs. Revenues, meanwhile, are
expected to grow by only $120 million or so, leaving a gap of $180
million to $230 million.
   Arkansas: Gov. Bill Clinton has proposed $211 million increase in
general taxes, mainly to increase spending on education, chiefly for
the salaries of public school teachers and the needs of colleges.
   California: Gov. George Deukmejian is to unveil the state's $40
billion-plus budget this week. Last year's budget finished in the
red, and this year's could too. Looming is a long-term debate over
insurance reform proposals following voter approval of Proposition
103, an insurance reform initiative requiring a 20 percent rate
rollback for most kinds of insurance and tougher state regulation of
insurers. A challenge is pending before the state Supreme Court.
   Colorado: Colorado's constitution prohibits deficit spending, but
for the past decade lawmakers have had to struggle, cutting programs
and raising taxes to keep the state in the black, and the outlook is
no different this year. Other issues are overhauling the state's
deteriorating highways and constructing new ones, education, the
environment and government efficiency.
   Connecticut: The state has a $134 million budget deficit this
year, and Democratic Gov. William A. O'Neill has said tax increases
will be necessary. Some programs and services also will have to be
cut back, he said. Other issues include school desegregation,
specifically in cities where there are high percentages of minority
students; criminal justice; and prison overcrowding.
   Delaware: The No. 1 issue is establishing a statewide paramedic
service. Highway safety may also become a pressing issue this year,
and there is talk that legislation calling for mandatory seat belt
use could be introduced again.
   Florida: Gov. Bob Martinez and legislative leaders agree that
Florida's overcrowded prisons and making do with existing revenues
are top challenges in the state this year.
   Georgia: Gov. Joe Frank Harris is proposing the first tax
increase since 1971, a 6 cents per gallon increase in the state's
motor fuel tax, now at 7.5 cents per gallon. The money would be used
to finance an accelerated road construction program and free funds
now being used for roads for other purposes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890108-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StateIssues-Glance 1stAdd   01-08 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Issues-Glance, 1st Add,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: other purposes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Hawaii: Improvements in the statewide school system probably will
top the agenda after a consultant's study gave the public schools
bad marks in many areas. Also likely are calls for tax cuts or
rebates in the face of a $400 million-plus surplus over the state's
$6 billion biennial budget.
   Idaho: What to do with a state budget surplus and how much money
to pump into the education system are the big issues. Idaho ended
the fiscal year June 30 with $14 million in the bank, and the
surplus at the end of the current fiscal year could easily be $20
million.
   Illinois: The General Assembly is confronted by whether to raise
taxes to expand state spending after two years of lean budgets.
Republican Gov. James R. Thompson campaigned unsuccessfully for a
state income tax increase for the past two years and has indicated
he will do so again this year. But there's been no sign of tax
increase opponents backing down. Also likely on the agenda is an
effort to repeal Illinois' premarital AIDS testing law.
   Indiana: The state must come up with a two-year budget for the
period beginning July 1, but it is in good shape financially.
Lawmakers will consider educational funding, ways to cushion the
impact of reassessing residential property, and what sort of state
gambling to allow, including a lottery or pari-mutuel betting on
horses.
   Iowa: The formula through which the state spends just over $1
billion on elementary and secondary education expires this year, and
legislators must devise a new one. This seems certain to lead to
battles between urban and rural areas. A similar formula allocating
money for highways also must be replaced. All sides agree that the
state faces a deficit _ estimated from $65 million to $120 million _
in the fiscal year beginning July 1, but there are no plans for a
tax increase.
   Kansas: Lawmakers must decide how much of a state surplus to
return to taxpayers, and by what method _ cutting income tax rates
or reducing property taxes. Another attempt to reimpose capital
punishment is expected.
   Kentucky: The Legislature is not scheduled to hold a regular
session this year, but Gov. Wallace Wilkinson has promised a special
session to address education. The state is on schedule to meet its
budget for this fiscal year and next, but lawmakers complain that it
is not enough to meet needs in education, prison overcrowding, human
services and other areas.
   Louisiana: The oil and gas industry-dependent state is still in
financial trouble, although not as deeply as when Gov. Buddy Roemer
took office in March, when it faced bankruptcy. The state approaches
the new fiscal year with $700 million less than needed to continue
services at the current level.
   Maine: Solid waste disposal, tax relief and health-care costs are
at the top of the agenda. To ease the burden of local property
taxes, Republican Gov. John R. McKernan is said to be considering
expanding the ``circuitbreaker'' program to relieve the hardest-hit
taxpayers and give direct grants to the fastest-growing communities.
   Maryland: What to do with the state surplus and how to manage the
Patuxent Institution are the top issues. Patuxent operates outside
the regular prison system and focuses on intensive treatment for
violent offenders. Critics say it is too lax, and the governor and a
legislative task force are drafting major reform legislation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
