<DOCNO> AP890108-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StateIssues-Glance 2ndAdd   01-08 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Issues-Glance, 2nd Add,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: reform legislation.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts: The state must resolve a projected shortfall of at
least $636 million in the current $11.6 billion state budget. It is
widely believed that Gov. Michael S. Dukakis will seek tax increases
and higher fees.
   Michigan: The budget, school financing and prisons are the top
issues. State revenues are expected to keep pace with the 4 percent
to 5 percent inflation growth in the 1989-90 fiscal year, but the
rising corrections budget, lower federal revenues and increased
costs for some federally mandated programs will swallow the growth.
   Minnesota: The state must prepare a spending plan for the
two-year period that begins July 1 and ends June 30, 1991, but this
time, it is solidly in the black. An increase in gang-related drug
activity and the slayings of two women in Minneapolis parking
garages have prompted calls for tougher criminal penalties.
Lawmakers also will consider setting up a state lottery.
   Mississippi: A proposal by Gov. Ray Mabus to reorganize the
government and the budget are the big issues. The governor has
proposed restructuring the state's more than 100 agencies, boards
and commissions into about 15 departments, but the plan has met with
a cool response.
   Missouri: Finding a way to improve the state's higher education
system and stepping up the war on drugs will be the two dominant
issues. The state has a balanced budget requirement, but revenues
are expected to grow only moderately and be more than eaten up by
the costs of court-ordered desegregation and Medicaid spending.
   Montana: The state must fashion a new system of funding public
elementary and secondary schools to replace a method that was
declared unconstitutional last year. The budget now before lawmakers
calls for spending that would outstrip revenues by $33 million in
the next two years.
   Nebraska: Property tax relief and aid to all levels of education
are the main topics to be debated. The state is looking at a $177
million surplus at the end of the fiscal year.
   Nevada: Adoption of a budget for the coming two fiscal years
along with a review of a $465,000 study of the state's tax structure
will occupy legislators. Althought Nevada has a projected surplus,
it is one of the fastest-growing states in the nation. Demands for
expanded services already have produced state agency spending
requests that would erase the surplus.
   New Hampshire: The big question is whether to create a public
energy authority with the power to take over Public Service Company
of New Hampshire and thereby keep electric rates under state
regulation. Public Service filed Chapter 11 last year and in its
reorganization plan seeks to re-form under federal regulation. That
would allow it to bypass a state law barring it from passing along
costs of its stalled Seabrook nuclear power plant to utility
customers.
   New Jersey: Rising auto insurance rates and ocean pollution are
expected to dominate debate. After New Jersey suffered a second
consecutive summer of beach closings because of high bacteria levels
and medical waste washing ashore, the Legislature passed a series of
measures to help clean up the state's ocean waters. However,
proposals to track the disposal of medical waste, impose tougher
penalties on polluters and create a powerful commission to protect
its coastline remain mired in legislative disputes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
