<DOCNO> AP890108-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StateIssues-Glance 3rdAdd   01-08 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Issues-Glance, 3rd Add,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: legislative disputes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   New Mexico: Education, particularly teachers' salaries, is of
greatest concern. Drug control and economic development are high on
Gov. Garrey Carruthers' list. The state is in good shape, with a
surplus projected at nearly $83 million for this fiscal year.
   New York: The overriding issue is the budget, with Gov. Mario
Cuomo also putting a high priority on fighting drug abuse. For the
fiscal year that ends March 31, Cuomo has said the state is still
short more than $1 billion on a state General Fund of more than $28
billion. For the next state fiscal year, there could be a budget gap
of at least $2.3 billion without special action.
   North Carolina: A budget crunch is the overriding issue. Although
a deficit is not envisioned, the expected surplus for fiscal year
1989-90, which begins July 1, is only $232 million and requests for
spending increases from state agencies exceed $3 billion. A
non-money issue is gubernatorial veto power; North Carolina is the
only state whose governor can't veto bills. Gov. Jim Martin wants
that changed.
   North Dakota: Proposed tax increases and a major overhaul of the
state government being pushed by Gov. George Sinner will keep
lawmakers busy. To increase spending for education and economic
development and to make up for sluggish state revenue, Sinner has
asked lawmakers to increase the personal income tax by a third,
boost the sales tax from 5.5 percent to 6 percent and raise the
gasoline tax from 17 cents to 20 cents a gallon. Sinner has also
proposed changes to streamline the government and public education.
   Ohio: School funding is at the top of the state's problems,
primarily because of an erosion of property taxes that has
heightened demand for additional state aid.
   Oklahoma: The state is continuing a slow recovery from the oil
bust. The budget this year will be $2.58 billion, up $137 million
from a year ago, thanks to an improving economy. Property tax reform
is the No. 1 issue.
   Oregon: Reforming school financing and fighting crime are the top
issues. The state's economy has been rebounding, and the governor's
proposed spending increase for 1989-91 comes to almost 20 percent.
   Pennsylvania: Automobile insurance reform and tax reform are
major questions. Legislation designed to ease the burden on property
owners by allowing municipalities to impose an income tax already
passed one session of the Legislature but must pass a second time
and be approved by voters in a referendum. The biggest controversy
could be where to locate a disposal site for low-level radioactive
waste.
   Rhode Island: Two years of budget surpluses may give way in 1989
to rockier economic conditions. Gov. Edward DiPrete plans to press
for a bill reviving the death penalty but may have trouble getting
it out of committee. Prison overcrowding, beach cleanup, and a
mandatory seat-belt law also are likely legislative topics.
   South Carolina: Auto insurance reform and waste disposal are the
hot issues; motorists' desire to lower the cost of insurance played
a key role in last fall's campaigns. A hazardous waste landfill used
by more than 30 other states as come under attack.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
