<DOCNO> AP890108-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StateIssues-Glance 4thAdd   01-08 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Issues-Glance, 4th Add,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: under attack.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   South Dakota: Funding for education, the budget and tax systems,
and expanding the state's lottery are the key issues. Republican
Gov. George Mickelson has asked the Legislature to increase state
aid to school districts in the budget year beginning July 1, with
more than half going to improve teachers' salaries.
   Tennessee: Prison overcrowding and the recommendations of a state
commission to reduce sentences for non-violent crime will be before
the Legislature. A 2- to 3-cent increase in the gasoline tax, now 17
cents a gallon, is proposed to keep the state's highway construction
program on schedule.
   Texas: The Legislature, convening for the first time since the
summer of 1987, faces a potential $1 billion budget shortfall. Also
high priority is reforming the state workers' compensation insurance
program. The state's public school finance system is under court
challenge because of the disparity between rich and poor districts.
   Utah: Lawmakers have the welcome task of how to allocate revenues
generated by a rejuvenating economy. Republican Gov. Norm Bangerter
is recommending a $19 million tax cut and a 3 percent pay raise for
public employees. Several bills dealing with AIDS also are expected,
including one to strengthen laws protecting AIDS patients' privacy.
   Vermont: The state faces a shortfall in its transportation fund
and has imposed a moratorium on paving projects. The governor is
expected to propose an increase in road revenues such as the
gasoline tax.
   Virginia: The state is building two new prisons to increase its
inmate capacity by 2,600, but corrections officials say the state
still will be at least 1,000 beds short in a few years. The economic
picture is good, but prison needs could swallow much of the extra
revenue. Gov. Gerald L. Baliles will ask the General Assembly to
return to taxpayers about a third of a $122 million budget surplus.
   Washington: The state must adopt a two-year budget for June 1989
through May 1991. The most controversial proposal would reduce the
sales tax and impose a flat-rate income tax. It has been defeated 10
times in the past.
   West Virginia: The state has tremendous financial problems and
needs to raise $290 million more to meet bills in the new fiscal
year, according to House Finance Chairman George Farley. A recent
state Supreme Court decision and a newly uncovered $212 million loss
in investments from 1987 have added problems of $390 million on top
of the $290 million. A tax increase is likely, with the most likely
candidate being a sales tax on food.
   Wisconsin: Adoption of a balanced budget is a must, and many hope
it will include property tax relief through additional state
revenue-sharing with local governments. Lawmakers also will address
constitutional amendments calling for a 10-year phaseout of the
property tax to support schools and to curb the governor's veto
powers. The state's mandatory seat belt law expires June 30.
   Wyoming: Raises for state workers, municipal financing and the
drinking age are top issues. State workers have gone without a raise
since 1985, except for a one-time $550 bonus, and officials are
becoming concerned that some of the best employees could leave for
the private sector. The state, however, faces a tight financial
situation.
</TEXT>
