<FIRST>r i AM-SKorea-Protests     01-08 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SKorea-Protests,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Say Government Suppressing Labor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Sunday fired tear gas to
disperse about 300 people protesting alleged government suppression
of labor movements.
   The protesters were among about 1,000 people who attended a rally
in downtown Seoul, denouncing what they called ``merciless
suppression'' of labor movements by the government of President Roh
Tae-woo.
   ``Get rid of Roh,'' protesters shouted as they marched after the
two-hour rally. Police detained at least three people.
   Protesters charged the Roh government had begun a crackdown on
labor as part of its effort to hold onto power.
   The marchers, blocked by hundreds of police at an intersection,
staged a sit-down protest. Most later dispersed voluntarily, but
some clashed with police a few blocks away.
   Police fired tear gas at about 300 who were hurling rocks as they
tried to march past the intersection. A few dozen people later
gathered near the U.S. Embassy in central Seoul to continue the
protests.
   Dozens of plainclothes police chased and arrested three of them.
</TEXT>
