<FIRST>r w AM-IrrigationSubsidies     01-08 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irrigation Subsidies,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gejdenson Attacks `Double Subsidies' For Western Farmers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is spending more than
$800 million a year on irrigation subsidies for Western farmers who
grow crops already in surplus, according to a congressional study.
   Administration officials acknowledge such subsidies exist, but
say they are a fourth a large as reported by a House subcommittee
staff study and stem from agreements that are 20 or 30 years old.
   The farmers in question are receiving water subsidies from the
Bureau of Reclamation to help irrigate part of their land to grow
surplus crops while receiving U.S. Department of Agriculture money
not to grow the same crops on other sections of their land, said
Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn.
   ``Farmers must choose their subsidy,'' said Gejdenson, who issued
the report. ``If they choose to continue to receive irrigation water
at the subsidized rate, they (should) not receive USDA commodity
benefits. If they choose to receive USDA commodity benefits, they
(should) have to pay the full, unsubsidized cost of providing
irrigation water to their farms.''
   Gejdenson, chairman of the House Interior and Insular Affairs
subcommittee on oversight and investigations, is urging
President-elect Bush to eliminate the ``double subsidies'' as a way
to help reduce the budget deficit.
   ``Double subsidies increase the cost of the USDA commodity
programs, place farmers who do not receive (federal) irrigation
water at a disadvantage in the marketplace and make it more
difficult for Congress to approve administration requests for new
and expanded water projects,'' Gejdenson wrote in a letter to Bush.
   But Interior Department officials, who dismiss the subcommittee's
estimates as heavily inflated, said the government's no-interest
contracts with farmers for the irrigation programs would be
difficult and costly to change.
   ``Most of our projects were built 20 to 30 years ago,'' said
Mitch Snow, deputy assistant secretary for water and science. ``We
cannot go back in there and fiddle with the contracts unilaterally.''
   ``It would probably cost more to implement'' than it would result
in savings, he said. ``We don't see that as beneficial.''
   The subcommittee report estimates that the Interior Department's
Bureau of Reclamation provides $2.2 billion annually in irrigation
subsidies, and that $830 million of that goes to farmers who receive
USDA surplus subsidies.
   Interior officials estimate the annual irrigation subsidy at $534
million, including an estimated $203 million to farms growing
surplus crops. Both estimates are less than one-quarter of the
subcommittee figures.
   Administration officials say the discrepancies stem from
differences in calculating interest rates and whether the cost of
building dams and canals should be included in the subsidy
estimates. The Interior Department estimates do not include those
costs.
   ``We're dealing in numbers,'' Snow said. ``You can get 52
economists in a room and come up with 110 answers, all of which are
defensible.''
   But the subcommittee, in its harshly worded report, charged that
the department purposely underestimated the estimates and later
interfered with the subcommittee's investigation by withholding key
irrigation subsidy documents.
   ``The department's `official' estimates of the irrigation subsidy
have no basis in reality and are politically motivated,'' the report
said.
   Peter Yeo, a subcommittee aide, said: ``If every member (of
Congress) knew what these irrigation subsidies were costing the
federal government, the political will for constructing or expanding
irrigation projects would be significantly less.''
   Snow denied the charges, saying that the Interior Department
cooperated fully with Gejdenson and that the differences in
estimates were legitimate discrepancies among economists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
