<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartoonist Berke Breathed stepped away from comic
pages, where his Opus the penguin has been searching animal testing
laboratories for his long-lost mother, and into a fur-protest march.
   ``This is the first time I've made the dangerous foray into
personal participation. I believe it's a less transient issue than
most, which is why I'm involved,'' Breathed said Saturday.
   ``A good place to start is trying to get people to stop wearing
furs,'' he said.
   The Pulitzer Prize-winning cartoonist, leading a crowd of nearly
400 through a pedestrian mall, carried a sign picturing a hunter
standing on a wolf's neck. The crowd chanted ``Shame on you'' at
shoppers sporting furs.
   Opus' odyssey through the laboratories of a cosmetic company
laboratories in Breathed's nationally syndicated comic strip,
``Bloom County,'' prompted a number of newspapers to pull the strip
during the series, which ran last month.
   ``It was as divisive as if I had been writing about abortion,''
Breathed said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country comedian Minnie Pearl, who has
undergone two operations for breast cancer, was honored by the
Nashville Academy of Medicine for her work to promote cancer
awareness.
   ``I do admire you,'' the Grand Ole Opry star, whose real name is
Sarah Cannon, told about 300 doctors Saturday night as she accepted
the academy's Community Service Award.
   ``Being a doctor is one of the greatest things that can happen to
a man or a woman. I could never achieve that status because I'm not
smart enough. All I could do was be a clown,'' Mrs. Cannon said.
   ``Some wonderful doctors took good care of me when I had breast
cancer. I'm glad I got this award because it gives me the
opportunity to say all these things.''
   Mrs. Cannon had two separate mastectomies and reconstructive
surgery in 1985. Since then, she has encouraged other women to pay
closer attention to signs of breast cancer.
