<FIRST>r w AM-Nancy-Fashion     01-08 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nancy-Fashion,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Being Honored By Fashion Designers Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stars of the U.S. fashion industry,
unabashed by disclosure that Nancy Reagan borrowed much of her
high-priced wardrobe while living at the White House, are honoring
her for ``outstanding contributions'' to fashion.
   Critics of the first lady's borrowing habits argue the practice
amounted to providing free advertising for the designers whose
clothes she wore.
   At a lavish dinner Monday at New York City's Metropolitan Museum
of Art, Mrs. Reagan is receiving the industry's equivalent of the
Oscar _ the Lifetime Achievement Award from the Council of Fashion
Designers of America.
   Mrs. Reagan's award is one of 10 bestowed by the group and will
be presented by ABC Correspondent Barbara Walters.
   The council, which is composed of many of the key fashion
designers in the country such as Calvin Klein, Ralph Lauren and
Donna Karan, voted Sept. 29 to give Mrs. Reagan the award.
   Oscar de la Renta, president of the council, said it recognizes
``the outstanding contributions she had made to American fashion.
During the past eight years as first lady, she has supported our
industry with grace and dignity and has represented our country both
here and abroad with great style.''
   Carolyn Gottfried, a public relations executive working on the
council dinner, said the controversy over the first lady's borrowed
wardrobe ``was not a problem'' for the designers.
   ``They are very supportive of her,'' she said, pointing to de la
Renta's statement as typical of the feeling many in the industry
have for the first lady.
   ``No, it's not a problem, otherwise they wouldn't be giving her
this award,'' she said.
   The group was founded in 1962 as a non-profit institution to help
promote American fashion. Proceeds from the awards dinner will be
donated to the costume institute at the Metropolitan, Ms. Gottfried
said.
   Mrs. Reagan has refused to speak at length about her practice,
first reported in Time magazine in October, of borrowing expensive
designer gowns and jewelry without making any reports on her
husband's annual financial disclosure forms.
   The magazine quoted one Los Angeles Designer, David Hayes, as
saying he'd made some 60 to 80 made-to-order outfits available to
the first lady over the years. She returned more than half and had
kept the others, the report said.
   At the time of the report, the first lady's spokeswoman, Elaine
Crispen, acknowledged that Mrs. Reagan had ``broke her little
promise'' to stop accepting items lent her by leading couturiers.
   When the practice first came into question in 1982, it was
decided that Mrs. Reagan's transactions would be reported on
President Reagan's financial disclosure form. The first lady also
vowed at the time to discontinue accepting the designer clothing.
   But the Office of Government Ethics has since reaffirmed a 1982
decision that such disclosures were not required under the Ethics in
Government Act. The ethics law requires reporting by an officials,
or by the official's spouse, of any loans in excess of $10,000 in
any year.
   Some of the gowns and clothing lent the first lady would carry
thousand-dollar price tags if purchased at full price from a fashion
house.
   After the disclosure, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Reagan considered the report ``a cheap political shot against the
first lady.''
</TEXT>
