<FIRST>u p AM-Governors-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0666 01-08 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0666,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Departure Of The Two Dukes Focuses Attention On Gubernatorial Races</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs next-to-last graf, now starting, ``In Florida xxx, to insert
state reference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two Dukes _ Michael Dukakis and George
Deukmejian _ are retiring at the end of their current terms and
their abrupt decisions are focusing attention on the gubernatorial
races that will be a critical political battleground the next two
years.
   Both men surprised observers by their timing if not their
decisions. Neither was expected to opt for lame duck status this far
ahead of the 1990 campaign.
   ``This will be my last term as governor of Massachusetts,''
Dukakis told a news conference on Tuesday. The 1988 Democratic
presidential nominee pointedly refused to rule out another run for
the White House in 1992.
   ``I did not come to public office to set some record of
longevity,'' said Deukmejian two days later in ruling out a run for
a third term as governor of California.
   Of the 10 largest states, New Jersey elects its governor this
year and the other nine do so in 1990. In five of those states _
California, Texas, Ohio, Massachusetts and New Jersey _ the
incumbent governor will not be seeking re-election.
   Gubernatorial elections are of special political interest the
next two years because those contests will have a major impact in
determining which party controls the redrawing of congressional
district lines after the 1990 Census.
   Twenty-eight of the nation's 50 governors are Democrats. Of the
36 races in 1990, Democrats will be defending 20 governorships,
Republicans 16.
   In California, for example, Democrats control the legislature. If
they capture the governor's office as well, they will be in a
position to repeat their post-1980 Census triumph when they picked
up five seats in the state's congressional delegation.
   The only Republican other than Deukmejian to hold statewide
office in California is Sen. Pete Wilson and there is speculation he
might run for governor in 1990, an office he sought unsuccessfully
in the past.
   Attorney General John Van de Kamp is regarded as the front-runner
for the Democratic nomination for governor, but former San Francisco
Mayor Diane Feinstein also is exploring a possible candidacy.
   On the Republican side, Peter Ueberroth _ leaving his post as
major league baseball commissioner on April 1 _ is the best known
potential candidate other than Wilson.
   Dukakis' decision, coupled with the announcement two days later
by Boston Mayor Ray Flynn that he wouldn't run for governor, offered
Republicans hope in a state where they rarely have any reason for
optimism.
   Andrew Card, tabbed for a top White House post in the Bush
administration, might reconsider and return to Massachusetts.
Another GOP name mentioned is former assistant U.S. Attorney General
William Weld.
   But the strongest names in the early speculation still are on the
Democratic side, including Rep. Joseph Kennedy, Lt. Gov. Evelyn
Murphy and former attorney general Francis Bellotti.
   The two 1989 governors races are in New Jersey and Virginia where
the incumbents, a Democrat in Virginia and a Republican in New
Jersey, are ineligible for re-election.
   Lt. Gov. Doug Wilder is the odds-on favorite for the Democratic
nomination in Virginia, while former Sen. Paul Trible, Rep. Stanford
Parris and Marshall Coleman are the best known GOP candidates.
   Big fields are forming in New Jersey for the race to succeed
Thomas Kean.
   The other 1990 races without incumbents are in Texas where GOP
Gov. William Clements has said he won't seek another term and in
Ohio where Democratic Gov. Richard Celeste cannot seek a third term.
   A big name looking at the governors race in Texas is George Bush
Jr., son of the president-elect.
   In the other big states, Democratic Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York,
re-elected with 65 percent of the vote in 1986, has said he expects
to seek a third term. Another Democrat, James Blanchard of Michigan,
drew 68 percent of the vote in 1986 and also is considered a likely
candidate for a third term.
   Republicans don't rule out upsetting first-term Democrat Robert
Casey in Pennsylvania, but concede they'd need a particularly strong
candidate to oust him if he doesn't stumble politically.
   The nation's senior governor is Republican Jim Thompson of
Illinois, now in his fourth term. Will he seek a fifth? Nobody
knows. A lot of Republicans were hoping he'd get a big job in the
Bush administration and move to Washington. Democrats always start
out optimistic against Thompson, but he's still in office.
   In Florida, GOP Gov. Bob Martinez is expected to seek a second
term and appears to have made a partial recovery from a rocky start
when he ran into a firestorm of criticism for backing a services tax
increase soon after taking office and then calling for its repeal
after businesses protested.
   Democrat Buddy MacKay, a former congressman who lost a close
Senate race in 1988 while George Bush was carrying Florida by a
landslide, is reported considering challenging Martinez.
</TEXT>
