<FIRST>r i AM-Libya-Planes     01-08 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Planes,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Says U.S. Aerial Photos Are Fakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ADABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya said Sunday that photographs
purportedly showing the downing of two Libyan jets are fakes that
``any small studio in Hollywood'' could produce.
   In a statement, the Libyan Embassy in Ethiopia's capital also
called on international public opinion to pressure the United States
``to stop its threats and aggressions.''
   Referring to the U.S. Defense Department as the ``Ministry of
War,'' the statement said the department had released altered
videotapes allegedly showing armed Libyan jets that were shot down
by Navy jets.
   The embassy said the Libyan planes were unarmed and on a routine
reconnaissance mission.
   Washington has provided television stations with videotape said
to be from Wednesday's attack, as taken by one of the U.S. aircraft.
The blurred film shows Libyan jets armed with what appear to be
missiles.
   On Friday, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Vernon
Walters, showed the U.N. Security Council two enlarged photos taken
from the videotape. He said the enlargements clearly showed the two
LIbyan Mig-23s were armed with missiles.
</TEXT>
