<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1451EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     01-08 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Iranian Shiites Take Control of Five Villages In Vicious Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian-backed Shiite Moslems captured five
key south Lebanon villages from pro-Syrian rivals in bloody
hand-to-hand fighting Sunday and seized control of a key area
bordering Israel's security zone, police said.
   A top commander from the pro-Syrian Amal militia, Mohammed
Hammoud, and his brother, Ahmed, were killed in a dawn raid on their
home by Hezbollah fighters loyal to Iran, said a police spokesman
who cannot be identified under standing rules.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization offered to deploy fighters
to separate the warring Shiites, but there was no immediate response
from either side.
   At least 35 people were killed and 66 wounded in house-to-house
combat in Kfar Hatta, Kfar Melki, Kfar Beit, Kfar Filla and Jbaa
villages in the former apple-growing district of Iklim el-Tuffah,
the spokesman said.
   That increased the overall casualty toll to 60 killed and 149
wounded since fighting erupted on New Year's Eve in Beirut and south
Lebanon between Hezbollah, or Party of God, and Amal, Arabic for
hope.
   Several hundred masked Hezbollah fighters, hurling grenades,
seized the villages strung along the main road from Sidon in a
four-hour battle.
   In a counterattack shortly before sundown, about 500 Amal
fighters rushed in from other districts of south Lebanon succeeded
in recapturing Kfar Hatta, police said. They gave no other details.
   The police spokesman said the Hammoud brothers died in their beds
during a grenade attack on the family residence in the Kfar Melki
village.
   Five other Amal militiamen manning a checkpoint in the same
village were captured and summarily ``executed'' by a Hezbollah
firing squad, he said.
   A hospital spokesman in Sidon, 25 miles from Beirut and the
provincial capital of south Lebanon, said the police casualty
estimate probably was too low.
   ``Some of the corpses brought in earlier were headless which
indicates the ferocity of the battle,'' he added, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Rescuers are now leaving the dead on the battlefield. They're
just bringing in the wounded, some of whom died on the way to
hospital.''
   Six rescuers _ three from Lebanon's Red Cross and three from the
Civil Defense department _ along with a policeman were wounded by
cross-fire in Kfar Melki and Kfar Hatta.
   The rival militias are fighting for mastery of Lebanon's 1
million-strong Shiite community, the country's largest sect.
   Hezbollah seeks to set up an Islamic state in south Lebanon. The
more secular Amal, loyal to Syria, rejects Iran's religious
influence over the Shiites.
   In Moslem-controlled west Beirut, Syrian troops from a
pecekeeping force sent patrols to halt inter-Shiite clashes in the
Noweiri and Bourj Abu Haidar residential districts. Police said no
casualties were reported.
   The village seizures left Hezbollah poised to attack the market
town of Nabatiyeh, the biggest Shiite urban center held by Amal,
lying just north of the ``security zone'' that Israel carved out for
itself in 1985 after withdrawing the bulk of its troops from Lebanon.
   ``If Nabatiyeh falls to Hezbollah, the fundamentalists will be in
control of most of south Lebanon's inland territory,'' the police
spokesman said.
   Capturing the town also would enable the pro-Iranian militia to
link the south with their main stronghold in the eastern Bekaa
valley and trap the Amal fighters along the Mediterranean coast, the
spokesman said.
   The killing of the Hammoud brothers was the second serious loss
in the Amal leadership in recent months. On Sept. 22, Daoud Daoud,
the militia's commander in the south and two other senior Amal
commanders were assassinated in south Beirut.
   Amal's chief, Nabih Berri, accused Hezbollah of staging the
killings.
   In Sidon, Yasser Arafat's representative said PLO fighters were
ready to help stop the fighting.
   ``I appeal to brethren in Amal and Hezbollah to respond to this
initiative, especially since the Israeli army is preparing a
large-scale aggression on south Lebanon,'' the representative, Zeid
Wahbeh, said.
   The PLO, which has ties with Hezbollah, last month reached a
peace pact with Amal to end years of fighting over control of
Palestinian refugee camps in Beirut and south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
