<FIRST>r i AM-Shultz-Shevardnadze     01-08 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shultz-Shevardnadze,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shultz Says Soviets Promise To Look Into U.S. Allegations Against
Libya</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chemical Conference, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Sunday the
Soviet Union promised to look into U.S. allegations that Libya has
built a factory to manufacture chemical weapons.
   Shultz said he outlined the U.S. case and offered a description
of the plant to Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze at a
meeting in Paris, where an international conference on chemical
weapons opened Saturday.
   Based on this ``general flow of evidence,'' Shultz said,
Shevardnadze pledged the Soviets would make their own inquiry.
   ``Since he cares about the subject and the Soviet Union cares
about the subject, there is no doubt the questions (to Libya) will
be pointed,'' Shultz told reporters just before leaving Paris.
   ``I think that is a constructive response,'' he added.
   Libya has denied the U.S. claim and said the facility 60 miles
southwest of Tripoli is intended to produce pharmaceuticals.
   Earlier, in a speech to the conference, Shevardnadze announced
his government will begin destroying its stockpile of chemical
weapons this year. Shevardnadze did not comment to reporters after
his meeting with Shultz.
   Shultz said the Soviets were given a statement of U.S. concern
over the plant during the visit to New York last month of Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev. But in the meeting Sunday with
Shevardnadze, ``they heard a little more about it,'' Shultz said.
   He said the U.S. goal is to prevent the plant, which the State
Department has said was on the verge of producing chemical weapons,
from achieving production of poison gas. ``If we can succeed in
that, we'll feel gratified,'' he said.
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi often has turned to the Soviets for
support when his country was the target of U.S. condemnation. But in
this case, Shultz said, the Soviets share the U.S. aversion to
chemical weapons.
   He said he believed the Soviets ultimately would back the United
States on the issue.
   Shultz sidestepped Shevardnadze's statements that the Soviet
Union had never transferred poison gas to other countries.
   ``I put that in terms of a pledge and I take it that way,''
Shultz said.
   In the past, the United States has alleged Soviet-backed forces
in Afghanistan used chemical weapons against U.S.-armed rebels.
   Shultz reminded reporters that President-elect George Bush had
proposed outlawing possession of chemical weapons five years ago at
a 40-nation disarmament conference in Geneva.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze also signed two accords, on drug
trafficking and on scientific cooperation, and toasted each other
with champagne afterward.
   The two countries are to share information on suspected drug
traffickers and methods of intercepting drugs. They also agreed to
cooperate in scientific research, including an exchange of experts.
</TEXT>
