<FIRST>r i AM-Libya     01-08 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Expels Most Journalists After Look At Exterior Of Disputed
Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan officials on Sunday expelled most of
the foreign journalists who poured into the country after two U.S.
fighter jets shot down two Libyan warplanes over the Mediterranean
Sea.
   At least 100 journalists, most of them American and European,
were put on an afternoon flight to Rome. However, at least 30 others
stayed on.
   The remaining journalists, including an Associated Press
reporter, managed to avoid government officials assigned to keep
tabs on them. Libyan officials said they could stay one more night.
   The expulsion orders came a few hours after the journalists were
taken Saturday evening to the site at the edge of the desert of a
plant that the United States claims was built to produce chemical
weapons.
   The journalists were not allowed inside the facility at Rabta, 60
miles southwest of Tripoli, and because it was already dark they
could see very little from the outside. The Libyan government
insists the plant is being constructed to manufacture medicine.
   Journalists saw a ring of surface-to-air missiles around the
plant and a radar station a few miles away. Libyan officials said
the defenses were put into place after President Reagan last month
said he could not rule out a military strike on the plant.
   Earlier Saturday, Col. Moammar Gadhafi showed up at the hotel for
an impromptu news conference in which he called for direct talks
with the United States to ease tensions. U.S. officials later
rebuffed the offer.
   When the journalists were returned Saturday evening from their
tour of the plant grounds, Libyan officials at the hotel told them
they had a few minutes to pack their bags for a flight to Malta. One
official said the reporters' rooms were needed for a delegation that
was arriving.
   Information Ministry aides assigned to monitor the foreign
journalists' movements told some of them on Saturday night they must
leave immediately on two special planes for Malta. Others heard only
from their colleagues that they were to be expelled. But no one was
forced out and by midnight it appeared the news corps would be sent
packing in the morning.
   Ministry aides refused on Sunday to explain the expulsion order.
One aide in the hotel lobby, when pressed for a reason, walked away
without a word.
   At least 100 journalists were put on two buses for the airport
for the flight to Rome on Sunday afternoon. Some avoided being put
on the flight by staying in their rooms or leaving the hotel.
   Those who remained behind were told to check out of their hotel
rooms and plan to take a charter flight Sunday evening to Malta.
   But the flight never materialized as reporters, camera crews and
photographers milled about the hotel lobby. Some drank tea, coffee
or other soft-drinks in the bar of this country where alcoholic
beverages are banned.
   Security guards stood by but took no action. Finally, the
journalists were allowed to check back into their rooms but were
told it was for one night only.
   On Thursday, the day after the Libyan planes were shot down, 30
foreign journalists who arrived in Tripoli on a flight from Rome
were refused entry and after 90 minutes were put back on the next
flight to Italy.
   Many of those journalists, some of them still without a visa,
returned the next day on a flight to Rome and were allowed into
Libya without any problem.
</TEXT>
