<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Egypt     01-08 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Egypt,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli, Egyptian Foreign Ministers Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid and
Israel's new foreign minister, Moshe Arens, met Sunday for talks on
a border dispute involving a strip of land along the Red Sea.
   The two ministers met during a five-day international conference
here on chemical weapons. It was the first time the two had met
since Arens became foreign minister last month.
   Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Abdel-Meguid said both
countries were ``interested in realizing a just and permanent peace
which is important for everybody, for all countries and people of
the region. We are moving in this direction.''
   Arens told reporters the two had discussed Taba, a disputed strip
of land at the northern tip of the Red Sea that Israel refused to
return to Egypt when it withdrew from the Sinai in 1982.
   A team of international arbitrators ruled late last year that the
disputed beach belonged to Egypt under a 1979 peace treaty, but the
specific borders still have to be determined by the two sides.
   Arens said further moves were expected ``in the coming days'' but
did not elaborate.
   Arens, speaking to reporters after the meeting, said the two
nations ``may be different in their viewpoints, it is also true and
important that we have direct contact.''
   Egypt is the only Arab country to have signed a peace treaty with
Israel.
   Abdel-Meguid visited Israel in July 1987 and met then-Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   Hazem Foda, a spokesman for the Egyptian Embassy, said the
ministers would ``meet again soon, either in Paris or elsewhere, and
their aides will meet together.''
   U.S. officials at the chemical weapons conference appeared
concerned at the hardening line of Arab and Third World countries
toward Israel.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz accused Israel of introducing
nuclear weapons to the Middle East. Israel has never responded
directly to allegations of its nuclear capacity, saying only that it
will not be the first nation to introduce nuclear weapons into the
region.
   Arens charged Iraq Sunday with ``hypocrisy and cynicism.'' He
added that Iraq was attempting to deflect attention from suggestions
that Baghdad has used toxic gas in its eight-year war with Iran.
   On his arrival in Paris for the conference Friday, Abdel-Meguid
said it was impossible to divorce chemical weapons from other arms
including nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
