<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Hirohito     01-08 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Hirohito,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Over Whether Royals Should Attend Emperor's Funeral</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito's death engulfed Britain's royal
family in a front-page debate Sunday about whether this country
should send representatives to the Japanese monarch's funeral.
   Many opposition lawmakers and World War II veterans still regard
Hirohito as an unpunished war criminal. They say it will insult
thousands of British servicemen if official representatives go to
the burial of the emperor, who died Saturday at age 87.
   About 27,000 British war prisoners died at the hands of the
Japanese in World War II, many during forced construction of the
notorious Burma railway.
   Both Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and Queen Elizabeth II sent
condolence messages Saturday that made no mention of the wartime
enmity, and both were expected to send representatives to the Feb.
24 funeral.
   The queen has asked her son and heir, Prince Charles, to
represent her in Tokyo, the British Broadcasting Corp. reported
Sunday.
   Buckingham Palace said no decision had been made, and the Foreign
Office said no government representative had been picked yet.
   The royal family already is being criticized for failing to send
a member to last week's memorial service in Lockerbie, Scotland, for
victims of the Dec. 21 Pan Am crash.
   ``If it wasn't good enough for them to come to the Lockerbie
service, I don't see why they should go all that distance out there
for a service for somebody that treated our servicemen ... in such a
way that people suffered for years,'' said Jim Campbell, chairman of
the Mid-Annandale Comrades Club.
   Former Foreign Secretary David Owen, who now leads the centrist
Social Democratic Party, said the queen should send Charles or her
daughter, Princess Anne, as a goodwill gesture.
   ``The problem is, the royal family has got themselves in a slight
mess,'' he told Britain's commercial TV-am. ``Not attending the
Lockerbie funeral was wrong and has caused understandable anguish
and criticism.''
   The debate was front-page news in most London newspapers.
   ``Royal Dilemma Over Hirohito'' was the headline in both The
Sunday Times and Sunday Express, which added ``After Lockerbie
memorial row, who will honor Japan's dead emperor?''
   Freddie Tompkins, spokesman for the 17,000-member Burma Star
Association, said he was ``absolutely flabbergasted'' by suggestions
Prince Charles might attend the funeral.
   ``This man was a monster and should have been tried as a war
criminal,'' he said of Hirohito.
   Ted Leadbitter, an opposition Labor Party legislator who served
as an artillery officer during the war, said: ``It would be quite
hypocritical, after what happened with all the atrocities, the
torture, the bloodshed and misery that our people went through, for
us to attend that funeral.''
   Alan Amos, a governing Conservative Party legislator, spoke of
the bitterness of prisoners' relatives.
   ``It is deeply insensitive and outrageous that messages of
condolence should be sent in relation to this war criminal,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
