<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissidents 1stLd-Writethru a0667 01-08 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0667,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Expels American, Canadian, Chinese Student for Dissidency</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with three accused leaving China, other
details. NO PICKUP.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of a U.S.-based dissident Chinese
group left Shanghai on Sunday after police accused them of breaking
the law, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   Xinhua said the three _ a Chinese-American, a Chinese-Canadian
and a Chinese student studying in the United States _ were heading
for other countries but did not specify if they had left China yet.
   American Huang Wencheng and Canadian Huang Han were ordered to
leave, Xinhua said. It was not clear if Tang Guangzhong, the Chinese
student and the only one of the three a Chinese citizen, also was
ordered out and whether he would be allowed to return.
   Officials at the U.S. and Canadian embassies said Chinese
authorities had not told them about the expulsions. The Huangs do
not appear to be related.
   Xinhua said the three acknowledged belonging to the New
York-based Chinese Alliance for Democracy, a group set up by a
former Chinese citizen in 1983 that advocates a democratic
revolution in China. Chinese officials have declared it an illegal,
reactionary organization and have banned its magazine, ``China
Spring.''
   The news agency said the men arrived in Shanghai early this month
carrying copies of ``China Spring'' and letters from an Alliance
leader to a jailed dissident, Yang Wei.
   Xinhua said they were guilty of ``illegal activities,''
presumably carrying the magazines and letter.
   Yang wrote for ``China Spring'' when he studied in the United
States. He was arrested when he returned to China and sentenced in
December 1987 to two years' jail for ``demagogical propaganda for
counterrevolutionary ends.''
</TEXT>
