<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Rebuilding     01-08 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Rebuilding,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Begins Rebuilding War-Ravaged Region</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has begun to rebuild homes and
factories in western regions hit hardest by its eight-year war with
Iraq, an official news agency said Sunday.
   An aide to Prime Minister Hussein Musavi said more than half the
money earmarked for reconstruction this year would be spent on
rebuilding war-destroyed cities and businesses, the Islamic Republic
News Agency said. The deputy's name was not given.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said much of the rebuilding
will take place in the Khuzestan, Ilam and Bakhtaran provinces. They
are all frontline western provinces that sustained heavy damage in
the war with Iraq.
   Iran accepted an Aug. 20 U.N.-sponsored cease-fire following a
series of military defeats, but efforts to reach a permanent
settlement have been deadlocked since November. Tehran has not
formally accepted that the war has ended, even though the government
is gearing up for post-war reconstruction.
   The government announced last month that it has allotted more
than $750 million for reconstruction during the current Iranian
year, which ends March 21.
   However, foreign analysts say it will cost $300 billion to 500
billion to rebuild the Iranian economy.
   In rebuilding industry, the government is giving top priority to
income-generating projects such as gas, oil and steel. It is also
concentrating on essential utilities, like power plants destroyed by
Iraqi air attacks.
</TEXT>
