<DOCNO> AP890108-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EarlyMardiGras 1stLd-Writethru a0655 01-08 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Early Mardi Gras, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0655,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Carnival Season for New Orleans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The early...', with 2 grafs to add detail on
earliest, latest Mardi Gras dates. Picks up 5th graf, About two...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas trees still sparkle in local homes,
but folks already are stocking up on Carnival beads and city work
crews are building parade stands for one of the earliest Mardi Gras
celebrations in years.
   ``We're going to be in more of a frenzy than normal, if that's
possible,'' said Blaine Kern, whose company makes most of the
Carnival parade floats. ``We'll barely have time to breathe this
year between parades, and that's not counting all the balls and
parties that will go on during the month.''
   Carnival begins on Twelfth Night, Jan. 6, with various balls and
parties, and ends Fat Tuesday, or Mardi Gras, the day before Ash
Wednesday. This year, with an early Easter, things got a head start
because Mardi Gras falls on Feb. 7.
   The early date leaves barely a month for reveling before Lent
when repentance descends on the city.
   The earliest Mardi Gras dates found in the Louisiana Almanac, on
a list from 1969 till 2000, is Feb. 7 _ this year and in 1978. Most
dates are middle to late February and five times Fat Tuesday occurs
during the first few days of March _ as late as March 7. So you can
say Mardi Gras falls this early only twice in the three decade
period.
   About two weeks before Mardi Gras, a series of parades in the
metropolitan area begin marking countdown before Shrove Tuesday. The
first of 50 metropolitan parades rolls on Jan. 21 this year.
   ``We made our deliveries right after Christmas. I think just
about everyone had it on the shelves by New Year's,'' said Dom
Carlone of Accent Annex Enterprises Inc., which specializes in Mardi
Gras items such as the colorful beads that are thrown by float
riders.
   Work crews began erecting bleachers along city streets Dec. 19,
and Officer Asa French, special events coordinator for the New
Orleans Police Department, said barricades used to control crowds
and traffic are being put in place this week.
   At Haydel's Bakery, Carnvial ``king cakes'' went on sale before
Christmas. David Haydel, president of the company, said bakers turn
out 2,000 to 3,000 cakes a day during the height of the party
season. This year they also hope to ship 100,000 nationally.
   King cakes _ big, donut shaped pastries covered with purple,
green, and gold sugar _ contain a small plastic baby. Tradition has
it that the person whose slice has the baby must be the host of the
next party.
   ``We started out shipping about 75 a day out in 1985. Last year
we shipped 8,000,'' Haydel said. ``This year we're advertising
nationally and we expect to sell better than $2 million of our Mardi
Gras packages.''
   Even though this year's festivities are compressed into a
shorter-than-normal time span, local authorities believe carnival
will see record numbers of people spend millions of dollars.
   ``This is turning out to be one of the best Mardi Gras in
history,'' said Beverly Gianna of the Greater New Orleans Tourist
Commission. ``And what we're seeing is that reservations for
accommodations began coming in much earlier than usual.'' She
attributed the interest to the exposure the city received last
summer as host of the Republican National Convention.
   Mardi Gras is expected to pour more than $2 million into the
hard-pressed local economy.
   ``People just love it,'' Gianna said. ``If they have less time
for it, they just go harder during that time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
