<FIRST>r i AM-AmazonKilling     01-08 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amazon Killing,0450</SECOND>
<UNK>Principal Suspect in Killing of Amazon Ecologist Surrenders to Police</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cattle rancher suspected by
authorities of ordering the killing of a prominent Amazon ecologist
surrendered to police because ``he was tired of living on the run,''
authorities said Sunday.
   Darly Alves da Silva, who police believe masterminded the
shooting death of ecologist Francisco Mendes, on Saturday walked
into the police station in the jungle town of Xapuri near the
Bolivian border, according to Mere Maia of the Acre state security
department.
   Mendes, 44, led a local rubber tappers union in Xapuri, where he
was shot outside his home on Dec. 22.
   The union, whose members collect rubber-making substances from
the trees, often block ranchers' efforts to clear rainforest by
standing in front of bulldozers with family and other community
members.
   Da Silva is the father of 21-year-old Darcy Pereira da Silva, who
has confessed to the killing. Two other brothers remain in custody
in connection with the case, and another one is sought by police.
   The father also was wanted by police in the southeastern state of
Parana in connection with several other murders.
   ``He turned himself in because he said he was tired of living on
the run,'' Antonio Gomes Campos, director of the Acre state
penitentiary system, told The Associated Press by phone from the
region.
   ``But he said he had no participation in the crime. He said he
heard about the killing and his son's part in the murder through the
newspapers.''
   Darcy Pereira de Silva told journalists he shot Mendes because he
``forced my father to live on the run from rubber tappers.'' He said
Mendes found out about the earlier warrant for his father's arrest
and forced him into hiding.
   Federal Police chief Romeu Tuma called the shooting of Mendes ``a
family decision'' by the da Silva clan.
   Later Saturday, the elder da Silva was taken to the Francisco de
Oliveira Conde penitentiary in the Acre state capital of Rio Branco,
Campos said.
   Mendes received the 1987 U.N. Global 500 award for top
ecologists. He was best known for devising ways to develop the
Amazon without harming the fragile ecosystem.
   The issue of how to develop the jungle, an expanse of rainforest
that covers about two-thirds of Brazilian territory, has often led
to bloody clashes between large landowners and politicians on one
side and peasant farmers on the other.
   Since 1980, more than 1,000 people have died in such land-related
conflicts, according to conservative estimates. The human rights
group Amnesty International says people were brought to trial in
only three cases.
</TEXT>
