<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-PlaneCrash 4thLd-Writethru   01-08 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Plane Crash, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0727,25,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plane En Route To Northern Ireland Crashes, At Least 10 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with 10, 129 reported on board, details of
crash, engine trouble; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jetliner bound for Northern Ireland with 129
people on board crashed Sunday while trying to make an emergency
landing on a highway in central England, authorities said. At least
10 people were reported killed.
   The Civil Aviation Authority said the British Midland Airways
Boeing 737-400 was en route from London's Heathrow Airport to
Belfast, Northern Ireland, when it reported engine trouble.
   Airline spokesman Michael Bishop said the pilot reported ``severe
vibrations in one of the engines'' and asked clearance for an
emergency landing at East Midlands Airport.
   ``He undershot the runway,'' Bishop said. He said the plane was
new and had been delivered 12 weeks ago. It was carrying 117
passengers and eight crew members, Bishop said.
   Civil Aviation Authority spokeswoman Ann Noonan said surivors
were being removed from the aircraft.
   The aviation authority said the plane disappeared from radar at
8:15 p.m. (3:15 p.m. EST) and crashed near Kegworth, about 100 miles
north of London, in Leicestershire county.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. reported 10 dead. It said the
plane crashed on a highway while on approach to East Midlands
Airport and that the Leicester Ambulance Service said there were
more than 120 casualties.
   An ambulance spokesman said the casualites included fatalities,
but it was not known how many. The Leceister fire brigade also
reported some fatalities but did not have a figure.
   The BBC said the plane appeared to be lying in three pieces.
Thirty ambulances were on the scene, along with 15 fire engines.
   It was the second major plane crash in Britain in three weeks. On
Dec. 21, a Pan Am jet bound for New York blew up over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the ground. That
jet had also left Heathrow. A bomb was blamed for the crash.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, quoted the
Leicester fire brigade as saying the plane hit an embankment on the
highway and that firefighters were rescuing some people.
   The Boeing 737-400 is a version of the Boeing 737 with a longer
fuselage and can carry 146 passengers. It was introduced last year.
</TEXT>
