<HEAD>South African Rebels Vow to Close Angolan Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African rebels fighting the
white-dominated leadership of their homeland pledged Sunday to close
their bases in Angola under an agreement with the Angolan government.
   Rebels of the African National Congress entered into the accord
to remove a possible setback for a U.S.-mediated independence plan
for Angola's southern neighbor Namibia, said ANC president Oliver
Tambo.
   Tambo said South Africa could point to guerrilla bases in Angola
as a reason for delaying the independence of Namibia, a territory
also known as South-West Africa which South Africa has administered
since World War I.
   The ANC leader spoke at a news conference in Lusaka, Zambia,
attended by visiting U.S. civil rights leader Jesse Jackson and
Andrew Young, the former U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
Jackson and Young are in Lusaka for a meeting of the African
American Institute scheduled to open Monday.
   Tambo gave no timetable for the shutdown of the bases and did not
say how many guerrillas were involved.
   The ANC, the main rebel group fighting South Africa's government,
has manned a number of training bases in Angola for several years.
It has mounted anti-government operations, however, through a number
of states on South Africa's northern border.
   Under the U.S.-mediated peace accords signed Dec. 22, Cuba agreed
to a phased withdrawal of about 50,000 of its troops from Angola. In
exchange, South Africa pledged to put into place an independence
plan for Namibia which calls for U.N.-supervised elections there by
Nov. 1.
