<FIRST>u i AM-France-Terrorists     01-08 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Terrorists,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial To Open For Terrorists Charged With Murder Of Renault Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of France's most notorious terrorists go on
trial Monday for the 1986 slaying of the president of the
state-owned automaker Renault who was gunned down in front of his
Paris home.
   Nathalie Menigon, 31, and Joelle Aubron, 28, are charged with
murder. Ms. Menigon's companion, Jean-Marc Rouillan, 33, and Georges
Cipriani, 38, are charged with complicity in the shooting of Georges
Besse on Nov. 17, 1986.
   If convicted by the special all-judge panel hearing the case, the
four face possible life sentences.
   All are considered leaders of the extreme leftist group Direct
Action, implicated in about 80 attacks between 1979 and 1988.
   In letters sent to several news organizations in Paris, Direct
Action on Feb. 11, 1987, claimed responsibility for killing Besse. A
later Direct Action statement said the shootings were not planned.
   The four were convicted in February 1988 of criminal association
and each sentenced to 10 years in prison. Ms. Menigon also received
a 12-year sentence for the attempted murder of two policemen on May
31, 1983.
   During the February trial, defendants shouted at judges, joked
among themselves and refused to answer questions.
   For about two months last year, the four held a hunger strike,
demanding an end to their solitary confinement. They were force-fed
intravenously and taken to trial in wheelchairs as their condition
deteriorated.
   Then-Justice Minister Albin Chalendon refused to yield to what he
called blackmail and the hunger strike ended after 74 days.
   About 50 witnesses are expected to testify during the five-day
trial, including Minister for European Affairs Edith Cresson, who
was overseeing the restructuring of Renault when Besse took over as
president. Prosecutors also are expected to call several people who
witnessed the murder.
   The four were arrested Feb. 21, 1987, at a farmhouse near Orleans
in a raid that also netted a stockpile of arms, explosives, money
and incriminating documents, including the original letter claiming
the Besse murder.
   The raid was part of a series of police sweeps which officials
believe snared all the organization's prominent members.
   When Direct Action first surfaced in 1979, its actions mostly
consisted of bombings or shooting at buildings housing French
government offices and those of other groups like the international
police organization Interpol, an Israeli bank, and the European
Space Agency.
   Assassinations began Jan. 25, 1985, with the shooting of Gen.
Rene Audran, the Defense Ministry official in charge of arms sales.
Ten days earlier, Direct Action announced it signed a pact with West
Germany's Red Army Faction for the development of a communist
guerrilla group in Western Europe.
   The groups claimed joint responsibility for a car bomb attack at
a U.S. air base outside Frankfurt in August 1985 that killed two
people and injured 20 others.
</TEXT>
