<FIRST>r a AM-WhoopingCraneService     01-08 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whooping Crane Service,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>30 People Attend Services For Whooping Crane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial service for a female whooping crane
that was shot last week drew about 30 environmentalists, who called
for a campaign to educate the public about endangered species.
   The bird was killed last Tuesday by a Houston hunter who said it
was accidental. It was the first reported shooting of a whooping
crane in 21 years.
   On Saturday, members of the Houston Audubon Society gathered at
the Edith L. Moore Sanctuary for the service to remember the bird
and to remind others of the fragile coexistence between man and
animals, said Jane Scheidler, the society's vice president for
environmental affairs.
   ``She was a wonderful, precocious bird,'' said Sandi Hoover,
Audubon executive director.
   Ms. Hoover said the bird was unusual because it was only 4 years
old but had already had a chick, while most female whoopers first
have chicks at age 5.
   About 200 whooping cranes exist today, and about 130 of them
roost each winter along the Texas Gulf Coast. Before conservation
efforts began, there were only 21 whooping cranes wintering in Texas
in 1941.
   ``I think this whooping crane incident is an indication of the
whole general problem out there,'' said Rex Wahl, a zoologist with
the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department's Natural Heritage Program
in Austin.
   ``For most people there's an unawareness, and a lack of
information. It just galls me that somebody doesn't care enough ...
to identify what they're shooting at.''
   The Houston businessman who shot the bird while at the Aransas
National Wildlife Refuge north of Corpus Christi said he mistook it
for a snow goose. The whooping crane was flying through heavy fog
with her mate.
   Government wildlife officials said they have not decided what
will happen to the hunter, though they say they may seek restitution
of $4,000 to $10,000.
   But Ms. Scheidler said the man should be forgiven because he
turned himself in to authorities, who then withheld his name.
</TEXT>
