<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Journalists     01-08 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Journalists,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banned Journalists Union To Seek Legal Status Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three hundred journalists who shunned a
union created for them after the 1981 martial-law crackdown voted to
seek reinstatement of their old organization, a representative said
Sunday.
   ``It's the right moment,'' said Stefan Bratkowski, president of
the former Association of Polish Journalists, on the second day of a
two-day meeting of the journalists in the basement of the
Association of Polish Authors' building.
   The journalists on Saturday drafted a letter to the Warsaw city
administration asking that the Polish Journalists Association be
registered because the official union ``is not fulfilling our
goals.''
   Several long-banned groups, such as the PEN writers club, have
recently received permission to function legally as the government
implements political reforms. The freer atmosphere has raised hopes
that the journalists' union might again be accepted.
   Broadcast and print journalists from around the country attended
the weekend meeting. Some of the participants were well known before
martial law but now work for obscure publications or in completely
different professions, such as construction.
   The Association of Polish Journalists, dominated by supporters of
the Solidarity trade union, was banned along with Solidarity in 1982
and replaced by the pro-martial-law Association of Journalists of
the Polish Peoples' Republic.
   At the same time, the government mounted a drive to win back
control of the media by purging from 500 to 1,000 journalists
nationwide for their political sympathies.
   Some writers who refused to join the new union were barred from
working at state-controlled publications. Others resigned rather
than submit to new editorial policies.
   In recent years, officials say the new union has consolidated its
position and now has nearly 8,000 members, as many as the old union
before its dissolution.
</TEXT>
