<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soviets     01-08 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviets,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Upgrading Israeli Consular Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will upgrade the status of the
Israeli consular mission in Moscow and view it as an ``address for
political activities,'' Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said Sunday.
   The move appeared to be part of a Soviet effort to improve
relations with Israel in order to help broker a Middle East peace
plan, said Arens.
   Arens said Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told
him during a meeting in Paris Saturday that Moscow will ``allow our
delegation to expand the volume and raise the level of its activity,
and to view it as an address for political activities.
   ``I think there's an important progress in it,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Paris with Israel army radio. Arens and
Shevardnadze are in the French capital for an international
conference on chemical arms.
   Shevardnadze said on Israel television the ministers decided to
``create normal working conditions for our consular groups in Tel
Aviv and Moscow ... and to hold personal meetings.''
   The Israeli delegation operates from the Dutch Embassy building
in Moscow, and the Soviet one from the Finnish Embassy in Tel Aviv.
   The Soviet Union cut diplomatic ties with the Israel following
the 1967 Middle East war, in which Israel captured territories from
Moscow's Arab allies, but relations have improved in the past two
years.
   A well-informed Foreign Ministry official told The Associated
Press the mandate of the Israeli delegation previously banned it
from holding any political discussions or working from the former
building of the Israeli embassy in Moscow, which it is now likely to
do.
   The group also had to renew visas every three months, a practice
now expected to be abandoned, said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Foreign Ministry sources indicated in private conversations the
Israelis may also be permitted to independently process visas for
Soviet Jewish emigrants and Jews wishing to visit Israel.
   The Soviets have allowed more Jews to emigrate to Israel and sent
a low-level consular delegation to Tel Aviv in July 1987. Israel was
allowed to send its own consular group to Moscow in July 1988.
   Arens said Israel and the Soviet Union remain far apart on how to
resolve Middle East conflicts.
   ``Mr. Shevardnadze presented the Soviet position about the peace
process and the PLO. Their stand is totally different from ours,''
Arens said.
   But he added: ``They feel they can contribute to the peace
process and want to convince us they can. Together with that, or
maybe because of that, they want to build channels of communication
more systematically.''
   The Soviet Union wants a U.N.-sponsored peace forum and says the
Palestine Liberation Organization must participate.
   Israel's Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, head of Arens' hard-line
Likud bloc, fears the conference might force Israel into territorial
concessions in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israel also refuses to negotiate with the PLO, which it views as
a terrorist group.
   Arens said Shevardnadze reiterated the Soviet appreciation of the
Israeli rescue and medical aid provided to the victims of the
earthquake in Armenia in December, and Israel's handling of the last
month's plane hijacking affair.
   The case involved five Soviets who traded hostage children for a
plane and about $2 million in cash and then flew the jet to Israel.
The Jewish state returned the hijackers, the plane and the money to
the Soviets on Dec. 3.
</TEXT>
