<HEAD>193 Haitians Aboard Sailboat Intercepted by Coast Guard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Coast Guard intercepted a 35-foot sailboat
with 193 Haitians aboard Sunday 550 miles southeast of Miami, an
agency spokesman said.
   It was the third time in as many days that federal authorities
had taken into custody Haitian refugees.
   Coast Guard crewmen found three of the passengers unconscious and
revived them, Petty Officer Luis Diaz said. He said the agency
planned to return the refugees to Port au Prince on Monday.
   On Friday, a sailboat carrying 94 Haitians ran aground in the
middle Keys, and most were detained in Miami for immigration
hearings.
   On Saturday, the Coast Guard took into custody 11 people aboard a
sailboat drifting off the coast of Cape Canaveral. Two passengers
were charged with attempting to smuggle illegal aliens into the
United States, and the other nine passengers _ including three
Haitians _ will be deported, officials said.
