<FIRST>u i AM-Crash-Relatives     01-08 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash-Relatives,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Wait For News</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clergymen provided comfort and
counsel at Belfast's airport on Sunday as nervous relatives waited
anxiously for details of a flight that never arrived.
   News that the Belfast-bound Boeing 737-400 jet crashed with 126
people aboard beside a highway in central England brought people
rushing to Aldergrove Airport outside the Northern Ireland capital.
   Many were unaware which of the frequent shuttles their relatives
had taken.
   Some were relieved to find their loved ones had missed ill-fated
Flight BD92, which took off from London's Heathrow Airport at 7:52
p.m. (2:52 p.m. EST).
   Others waited for news of the survivors. A woman sobbed quietly
in a corner of the shiny new terminal, recently opened for
international traffic after a major refurbishment.
   ``There is a spirit of anxiety and of course a lot of patience is
being exercised,'' said the Rev. Ian Paisley, the Presbyterian
minister and a leading politician in the province.
   He spoke to relatives at Aldergrove, a 40-minute drive from
Belfast. The religious and political violence between Roman Catholic
and Protestant extremists dictates the strictest airport security in
Britain.
   ``People realize they must just wait and hope and pray their
loved ones are going to be all right,'' he said. ``In a situation
like this you always prepare yourself for the worst but the
relatives are bearing up very well. The airline is doing everything
possible.''
   Jack McConnell, chief executive of Northern Ireland Airports,
said relatives were ``very, very distressed.'' He helped set up a
hotline to Loughborough, 6 miles from the scene of the crash, to
make sure relatives were kept informed.
   A clergyman, one of a number at the airport along with doctors
standing by, told of a survivor able to get a message to his mother.
   Rev. James Barrett, a priest from Belfast, said: ``That poor
woman was mighty relieved to hear such wonderful news. Her son got
the message through fairly quickly. He appears to be OK.''
   Most people at the airport were too distraught to speak, but one
who got good news stopped to chat to a reporter.
   Richard Laird received word that his daughter Karen, 19, had made
the later flight after a New Year holiday in London.
   ``She was on time to get that flight but she decided against
changing and waited for the 9:20. We feel terribly relieved,'' he
said. ``We feel very sorry for what the relatives are going through
right now. It must be harrowing because for 15 minutes _ before it
was confirmed Karen was safe _ we were in an awful state.''
   A senior Northern Ireland government official, Industry Minister
Peter Viggers, was at first feared to be aboard the crashed plane,
but it soon transpired that he had taken the next flight.
   A few relatives gathered at Heathrow airport, and chaplains stood
by to help.
   A Belfast man who dropped off a cousin to catch the flight said,
``I've come down to try to find out what happened to him but they
can't give me any information. I'm going back to London to wait by
the phone and pray he's all right.''
</TEXT>
