<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolShooting     01-08 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Shooting,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Convicted Of 2nd-Degree Murder In Death Of Assistant Principal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury convicted a teen-ager of
second-degree murder Sunday for a shooting spree in a high school
cafeteria last year that left an assistant principal dead and two
other adults wounded.
   Jurors deliberated approximately 8{ hours over Saturday and
Sunday before finding Jason Harless, 16, guilty of killing Richard
Allen.
   Harless also was convicted on charges for wounding two other
members of the school's faculty and for shooting at Pinellas Park
police officers as he fled the school.
   Patrick Doherty, the teen-ager's defense attorney, said he and
his client were pleased that the jury returned a lesser conviction
in Allen's death.
   ``There's a profound difference between murder two and murder
one,'' he said Sunday. ``There's an array of choices that the judge
can choose for sentencing.''
   Harless faces a maximum punishment of life in prison, rather than
the death penalty that first-degree murder can carry in Florida.
Circuit Judge Claire Luten set sentencing for March 10.
   Harless and a friend, Jason McCoy, ran away from home Feb. 10,
taking along two .38-caliber handguns from a neighbor's house. They
went to say goodbye to their friends the next day at Pinellas Park
High.
   Harless admits punching two school administrators, pointing a gun
at one of them and shooting student-teacher Joseph Bloznalis. But he
says he doesn't remember shooting Allen and assistant principal
Nancy Blackwelder when they tried to take away a gun from McCoy in
the school cafeteria.
   Harless said he regained his memory as he ran from the school,
firing three shots at two Pinellas Park police officers.
   Harless had been charged with first-degree murder, two counts of
attempted first-degree murder and aggravated battery. A charge of
burglary was dismissed before the case went to the jury Saturday.
   Doherty argued Saturday that Harless was in a ``dissociative
state'' during the shooting and was not responsible for his actions.
   During the three-hour closing arguments, Harless sat quietly, his
head bowed. His mother sat nearby, across from Allen's family,
including his three children.
   ``What happened in that four to 10 seconds has changed the lives
of a lot of people, and it's a tragedy,'' the defense attorney said.
   Prosecutor Mary McKeown argued that Harless was a vicious,
calculating young man who deliberately shot and killed Allen.
   ``Maybe it was because he had an alcoholic father who beat his
mother,'' she told the jury Saturday. ``Does that excuse his crime?
He's a kid who has made choices, and the choices have all been
wrong. ... He gets angry and violent and that's the bottom line.''
</TEXT>
