<FIRST>r i AM-NewZealand-Hirohito     01-08 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Zealand-Hirohito,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Says Emperor Deserved Execution For War Crimes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Emperor Hirohito of Japan
should have been tried and executed as a war criminal after World
War II, Defense Minister Bob Tizard said Monday.
   Tizard, expressing concern about ``unctuous statements'' from
around the world following the emperor's death from cancer on
Saturday, argued that Hirohito ``should have been shot or publicly
chopped up at the end of the war.
   ``For New Zealand to express any sympathy grates against my back
teeth,'' said Tizard, who served in New Zealand's air force during
the war.
   Prime Minister David Lange issued a statement later, saying
Tizard was expressing personal views not endorsed by the Labor
government.
   Tizard, a former deputy prime minister and the Labor's
government's longest serving member of Parliament, told reporters he
blamed Hirohito for the deaths of ``a few hundred of my friends and
thousands of others who were butchered by the Japanese after being
taken prisoner.''
   He said he was ``grateful'' for the dropping of atomic bombs on
Japan by the United States, adding he did not think his comments
would affect New Zealand's trading relationship with Japan.
   ``They trade with us only when and if they can't get a better
deal from anyone else,'' he said.
   Japan is New Zealand's largest overseas market and exports to
that country last year totaled $1.7 billion.
   Tizard claimed not to hold any grudges against the Japanese
people.
   ``I don't think the sins of the father should be visited on the
son,'' he added.
</TEXT>
