<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Contra     01-08 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Contra,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista Radio Blames Rebel Leader's Killing on Contra Infighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's official radio station
on Sunday blamed the slaying of an anti-Sandinista guerrilla leader
in Honduras on rebel infighting.
   The killing Saturday of Manuel Adan Rugama Acevedo ``is another
product of the deep divisions that exist (among rebel forces), as
much in Honduras as in Miami,'' said the broadcast of Radio Sandino,
voice of Nicaragua's ruling National Sandinista Liberation Front.
   Leaders of the anti-Sandinista rebels known as the Contras,
however, blame Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government for the
killing.
   A doctor by training, Rugama, 39, was a Contra regional
commander, an ex-secretary of the Contras' Commanders Council and a
military spokesman for the Nicaraguan Resistance, the rebels'
political wing.
   Rugama was killed Saturday morning by two unidentified men in a
drive-by shooting in the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa. Police
said his body was riddled with 26 bullet wounds by an Israeli-made
Uzi machine gun.
   Rugama reportedly attended a Contra leadership meeting in
Tegucigalpa in the morning and was on his way to a friend's birthday
party when he was slain on a highway just west of the capital.
   He was driving alone in an open Jeep when two men in a passing
vehicle opened fire. Police later found Rugama's body on the highway
next to the vehicle.
   Sandinista officials on Sunday continued to refuse comment on the
killing. One government spokesman told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview: ``We don't know anything about it.''
   But the Radio Sandino broadcast indicated that Rugama, also known
as ``Commander Aureliano,'' may have been killed by another
Nicaraguan guerrilla. Radio Sandino said Rugama previously had been
accused by a fellow rebel commander of selling arms to Salvadoran
guerrillas.
   The broadcast also said that in early 1988 several Contra
commanders rebelled against the group's leadership and ``in some
camps there were confrontations with gunshots.''
   Enrique Bermudez, a member of the Resistance directorate, told
reporters in Tegucigalpa on Saturday that he believed the slaying
was ``perpetrated by by the communists of the Sandinista Front, who
are our only enemies.''
   In Tegucigalpa, police on Sunday continued their search for
Rugama's killers.
</TEXT>
