<FILEID>AP-NR-01-08-89 2311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AlaskaQuakes     01-08 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska Quakes,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pair Of Quakes Jolt Aleutian Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two moderate earthquakes jolted an area
southeast of Adak in the Aleutian Islands on Sunday, but there were
no reports of damage or injuries, the Alaska Tsunami Warning Center
reported.
   The first quake occurred at 10:57 a.m. and was centered 90 miles
southeast of Adak, center spokesman Wayne Jorgensen said. It
measured 5.6 on the Richter scale, he said.
   The second temblor occurred at 11:26 a.m. and was located in the
same general vicinity, he said. It measured 4.8 on the scale.
   Neither was felt at Adak, the nearest populated area, he said.
There also were no reports of tsunamis, the huge sea waves that can
devastate islands and coastal communities after earthquakes.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude; a reading of 7.5 means ground motion is 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of magnitude 3.5 can cause slight damage, 4 is
capable of moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage,
7 widespread damage and 8 tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
