<FIRST>r f AM-Venezuela-Debt     01-08 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Debt,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Venezuelan Central Bank Head To Meet With Greenspan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Venezuela's central bank
plans to meet with Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan in
New York on Monday to discuss upcoming debt negotiations, according
to a published report.
   The Caracas daily El Nacional quoted unidentified sources Sunday
as saying Mauricio Garcia Araujo will seek the Fed's participation
as mediator in the talks with creditor banks.
   Venzuela is looking for more favorable terms on rescheduling
repayment of Venezuela's $33 billion debt, the fourth largest in
Latin America, said El Nacional.
   Venezuela decided last week to suspend payment of principal on
its debt due to a drop in the country's international reserves
brought about by falling oil prices in 1988 and continued government
subsidies of imports.
   A Venezuelan negotiating team is scheduled to meet with creditor
bank representatives Thursday in New York's Chase Manhattan Corp.
bank headquarters.
</TEXT>
